# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: rifled-breech-loader
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:rifled-breech-loader/1-inch-nordenfelt-gun] The **1-inch Nordenfelt gun** was an early quick-firing light gun intended to defend larger warships against the new small fast-moving torpedo boats in the late 1870s to the 1890s.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/1-inch-nordenfelt-gun] The gun was an enlarged version of the successful rifle-calibre Nordenfelt hand-cranked "machine gun" designed by Helge Palmcrantz and was intended to combine its rapid rate of fire with a projectile capable of deterring attacking torpedo boats.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/1-inch-nordenfelt-gun] The gun fired a solid steel bullet with hardened tip and brass jacket: under the terms of the St.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/1-inch-nordenfelt-gun] Petersburg Declaration of 1868, exploding shells weighing less than 400 grams were not allowed to be used in warfare between the signatory nations.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/1-inch-nordenfelt-gun] The gun was used in one, two and four-barrel versions.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/1-inch-nordenfelt-gun] The ammunition was fed by gravity from a hopper above the breech subdivided into separate columns for each barrel.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/1-inch-nordenfelt-gun] The gunner loaded and fired the multiple barrels by moving a lever on the right side of the gun forward and backwards.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/1-inch-nordenfelt-gun] Pulling the lever backwards extracted the fired cartridges, pushing it forward then loaded fresh cartridges into all the barrels, and the final part of the forward motion fired all the barrels, one at a time in quick succession.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/1-inch-nordenfelt-gun] Hence the gun functioned as a type of volley gun, firing bullets in bursts, compared to the contemporary Gatling gun and the true machine guns which succeeded it such as the Maxim gun, which fired at a steady continuous rate.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/1-inch-nordenfelt-gun] The gunner was occupied with manually operating the loading and firing lever, while the gun captain aimed the gun and operated the elevation and training handwheels.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/7-5-cm-pak-40] The **7.5 cm Pak 40** (*7,5 cm Panzerabwehrkanone 40*) was a German 75 millimetre anti-tank gun of the Second World War.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/7-5-cm-pak-40] The gun was developed in 1939–1941 and entered service in 1942.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/7-5-cm-pak-40] With 23,303 examples produced, the Pak 40 formed the backbone of German anti-tank guns for the later part of World War II, mostly in towed form, but also on a number of self propelled artillery such as the *Marder* series of *Panzerjäger*.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/7-5-cm-pak-40] A modified version of the gun designed specifically for vehicle-mounting was the 7.5 cm KwK 40, which differed primarily in using more compact ammunition, thereby allowing more rounds to be carried inside the vehicles.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/7-5-cm-pak-40] The KwK 40 armed many of the German mid-war tank designs such as the Panzer IV, as well as tank destroyer designs, replacing the Pak 40 in the latter role.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/7-5-cm-pak-40] The Pak 40 may be referred to as the **7.5 cm L/46**, referring to its calibre and the barrel's length in calibres.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/7-5-cm-pak-40] There were two versions of the KwK 40, which would be referred to as the 7.5 cm L/43 or 7.5 cm L/48.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/7-5-cm-pak-40] Development of the Pak 40 began after reports of new Soviet tank designs began to reach Berlin in 1939.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/7-5-cm-pak-40] The German army was equipped with the 3.7cm Pak 36 at the time.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/7-5-cm-pak-40] A replacement 5 cm Pak 38 was still in testing at this point, but it appeared it would not be powerful enough to deal with these newer designs.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/7-5-cm-pak-40] Contracts were placed with Krupp and Rheinmetall to develop what was essentially a 7.5 cm version of the Pak 38.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/7-5-cm-pak-40] However, while the Pak 38 made extensive use of light alloys to reduce overall gun weight, these were now earmarked for aircraft production to supply the *Luftwaffe*.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/7-5-cm-pak-40] As a result, the Pak 40 used steel throughout its construction and was proportionally heavier than the 5 cm model.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/7-5-cm-pak-40] To simplify production, the Pak 38's curved gun shield was replaced by one using three flat plates.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/7-5-cm-pak-40] A version called the 7.5 cm FK 7M59 was proposed towards the end of the war to fill a dual-purpose role of field gun and anti-tank gun.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/7-5-cm-pak-40] The carriage was modified to provide +35° of elevation which increased maximum range to 13,300 m (14,500 yd).
[src:rifled-breech-loader/7-5-cm-pak-40] Another dual purpose variant was the 7.5 cm FK 7M85 which used the gun and recoil system of the Pak 40 on the carriage of the 10 cm le FH 18/40.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/7-5-cm-pak-40] The project was initially given low priority, but following the invasion of the USSR in 1941 and the appearance of heavily armoured Soviet tanks such as the T-34 and KV-1, it was given an increased priority.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/7-5-cm-pak-40] The first production guns were delivered in February 1942.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/7-5-cm-pak-40] In April 1942, the *Wehrmacht* had 44 guns in service; by 1943, the Pak 40 formed the bulk of German anti-tank artillery.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/7-5-cm-pak-40] The Pak 40 was the standard German anti-tank gun until the end of the war, and was supplied by Germany to its allies.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/7-5-cm-pak-40] Some captured guns were used by the Soviet Red Army.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/7-5-cm-pak-40] 23,303 Pak 40s were produced, and about 3,500 more were used to arm tank destroyers.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/7-5-cm-pak-40] The unit manufacturing cost amounted to 2,200 man-hours at 12,000 RM.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/7-5-cm-pak-40] The usual prime movers were Opel Blitz lorry, Raupenschlepper Ost tracked tractor, SdKfz 11 medium halftrack and SdKfz 251 armoured halftrack.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/7-5-cm-pak-40] A lighter version of the Pak 40 was used as the *BK 7,5* automatic "weapon system" in the Henschel Hs 129B-3 and the Junkers Ju 88P-1 ground attack aircraft.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/7-5-cm-pak-40] This version of the Pak 40 was the heaviest of the *Bordkanone* series of heavy calibre aircraft guns, incorporating a twelve-round magazine.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/7-5-cm-pak-40] This version of the gun was also intended as a production fitment for a possible He 177A-3/R5 heavy bomber adaptation late in 1942, originally prototyped in the field with BK 5 cannons, themselves adapted from the 5 cm KwK 39 tank gun from the Panzer III.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/7-5-cm-pak-40] During the second half of World War II, some Romanian anti-tank platoons each had three Pak 40 guns.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/7-5-cm-pak-40] These were used interchangeably with Romania's own 75 mm Reșița Model 1943 anti-tank gun.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/7-5-cm-pak-40] Italy also received the Pak 40 from Germany since March 1943, the gun was renamed *Cannone da 75/43 Mod.40*, at least 66 guns were delivered before the Italian armistice.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/7-5-cm-pak-40] The weapon was effective against almost every Allied tank until the end of the war, only struggling to penetrate heavier vehicles like the Russian IS tanks, the American M4A3E2 Sherman 'Jumbo' assault tank and M26 Pershing, and later variants of the British Churchill tank.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/7-5-cm-pak-40] The Pak 40 was much heavier than the Pak 38; its decreased mobility meant that it was difficult or even impossible to move without an artillery tractor on boggy ground.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/7-5-cm-pak-40] However, near Caen in June 1944, Oberfeldwebel Hans Erich Braun of Panzerjäger-Abteilung 38 of 2nd Pz div. reported about his battery supporting an attack by the 304th Pz Grenadier regiment near Caumont.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/7-5-cm-pak-40] Keeping up with the grenadiers, Braun's men moved their remaining two guns by hand through incredibly difficult terrain.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/7-5-cm-pak-40] The Pak 40 was first used in the USSR where it was needed to combat the newest Soviet tanks.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/7-5-cm-pak-40] It was designed to fire the same low-capacity APCBC, HE and HL projectiles that had been standardized for use in the long barrelled *Kampfwagenkanone* KwK 40 tank-mounted guns of the mid-war and later marks of the Panzer IV medium tank.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/7-5-cm-pak-40] In addition, there was an APCR shot (*Panzergranate* 40) for the Pak 40, a munition which - reliant on supplies of tungsten - eventually became very scarce.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/7-5-cm-pak-40] According to the German *Panzertruppen* news journal, 5,000 APCR rounds were expected in Dec.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/7-5-cm-pak-40] 1942 as replenishment for the Winter offensive.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/7-5-cm-pak-40] The main differences amongst the rounds fired by 75 mm German guns were in the length and shape of the cartridge cases as well as the primers used.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/7-5-cm-pak-40] The 7.5 cm KwK 40 (75x495mm) used in tanks had a fixed cartridge case twice the length of that used by the 7.5 cm KwK 37, the short barrelled 75 mm used on earlier tanks, and the 7.5 cm Pak 40 cartridge was a third longer than that used by the KwK 40.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/7-5-cm-pak-40] The Pak 40 used a percussion primer, while the vehicle mounted 75 mm guns used electrical primers.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/7-5-cm-pak-40] Other than minor differences with the projectiles' driving bands, all German 75 mm guns used the same 75mm projectiles.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/7-5-cm-pak-40] The longer cartridge case of the Pak 40 allowed a larger charge to be used and a higher velocity for the PzGr 39 armour-piercing capped ballistic cap round to be achieved.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/7-5-cm-pak-40] The only 75mm fighting vehicle gun in general use by Germany that possessed a longer barrel than the Pak 40, the 7.5 cm KwK 42 on the Panther tank, could achieve a higher muzzle velocity of 935 m/s (3,070 ft/s) using more propellant in a larger cartridge fixed to it for the KwK 42's use.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/7-5-cm-pak-40] For unknown reasons, some 75 mm APCBC cartridges appear to have been produced with a charge that gave a muzzle velocity of about 770 m/s (2,500 ft/s).
[src:rifled-breech-loader/7-5-cm-pak-40] The first documented firing by the US of a Pak 40 recorded an average muzzle velocity of 776 m/s for its nine most instrumented firings.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/7-5-cm-pak-40] Probably because of these results, period intelligence publications ("Handbook on German Military Forces") gave about 770 m/s as the Pak 40 APCBC muzzle velocity.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/7-5-cm-pak-40] German sources differ; the Official Firing Table document for the 75 mm KwK 40, StuK 40 and the Pak 40 dated October, 1943, gives 770 m/s on one of the APCBC tables.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/7-5-cm-pak-40] An armour-piercing, capped, ballistic cap (APCBC) projectile with explosive filler and tracer.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/7-5-cm-pak-40] An armour-piercing, composite rigid (APCR) projectile with a sub-calibre tungsten core.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/7-5-cm-pak-40] A high-explosive anti-tank (HEAT) projectile with a shaped charge.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/7-5-cm-pak-40] After the war, the Pak 40 remained in service in several European armies, including Albania, Bulgaria, Czechoslovakia, Finland, Norway, Hungary and Romania.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/7-5-cm-pak-40] In 1955, the USSR supplied 33 captured guns to Austria.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/7-5-cm-pak-40] They were kept in service into the 1960s.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/7-5-cm-pak-40] North Vietnam also received some during the Vietnam War.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/7-5-cm-pak-40] Six ex-Portuguese Army Pak 40s divided into two artillery detachments were stationed in Dili during the Indonesian invasion of East Timor in 1975.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/aizu] It was part of Mutsu Province; the area once was part of Iwase Province created during the reign of Empress Genshō.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/aizu] The *Yōrō Ritsuryo* established the Iwase Province in 718 through the division of the Michinoku Province (Mutsu Province).
[src:rifled-breech-loader/aizu] It was composed of five districts of Shirakawa (白河), Iwase (石背), Aizu (会津), Asaka (安積) and Shinobu (信夫).
[src:rifled-breech-loader/aizu] The area encompassed by the province reverted to Mutsu some time between 722 and 724.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/aizu] During the Edo period, Aizu Domain (会津藩, *Aizu-han*) was a feudal domain under the Tokugawa shogunate which ruled most of the region from Aizuwakamatsu Castle.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/aizu] Following the Meiji restoration, it became part of the short-lived Iwashiro Province before becoming a region of Fukushima Prefecture.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/aizu] Although never an official province in its own right, Aizu has a very strong regional identity.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/aizu] The following list is alphabetized by Japanese name order (i.e. surname followed by given name).
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anglo-german-naval-arms-race] The arms race between Great Britain and Germany that occurred from the last decade of the nineteenth century until the advent of World War I in 1914 was one of the intertwined causes of that conflict.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anglo-german-naval-arms-race] With the support of the Kaiser Wilhelm II, Tirpitz began advancing a series of laws to construct an increasing number of large surface warships.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anglo-german-naval-arms-race] The construction of HMS *Dreadnought* in 1906 prompted Tirpitz to further increase the rate of naval construction.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anglo-german-naval-arms-race] While some British observers were uneasy at German naval expansion, alarm was not general until Germany's naval bill of 1908.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anglo-german-naval-arms-race] The British public and political opposition demanded that the Liberal government meet the German challenge, resulting in the funding of additional dreadnoughts in 1910 and escalating the arms race.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anglo-german-naval-arms-race] Maintaining Europe's largest army and second-largest navy took an enormous toll on Germany's finances.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anglo-german-naval-arms-race] Theobald von Bethmann Hollweg, German chancellor from 1909, undertook a policy of détente with Britain to alleviate the fiscal strain and focus on the rivalry with France.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anglo-german-naval-arms-race] Under Bethmann Hollweg, and particularly from 1912 onwards, Germany abandoned the dreadnought arms race and focused on a commerce raiding naval strategy to be conducted with submarines.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anglo-german-naval-arms-race] The success of German submarine warfare during World War I had great influence on German Naval policy in the lead up to the Second World War, with the utilisation of both U-boats and fast, well armoured battlecruisers for commerce raiding being the primary task of the Kriegsmarine.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anglo-german-naval-arms-race] Britain had the largest navy in the world and its policy was to ensure the Royal Navy was at least the size of the next two largest navies combined, known as the two-power standard.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anglo-german-naval-arms-race] Britain's economy was dependent on the ability to ship in raw materials and export out a finished product.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anglo-german-naval-arms-race] By 1900, 58% of calories consumed by Britain's population came from overseas, meaning that an inability to guarantee free movement on the seas would result in food shortages.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anglo-german-naval-arms-race] Even before the German naval challenge, British political and military leaders mused about catastrophic economic, social, and political consequences if the Royal Navy could not guarantee British freedom of action.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anglo-german-naval-arms-race] Worry about Britain's ability to defend itself became the focus of the invasion literature genre, which began in 1871, remained popular to World War I, and was highly influential on public opinion.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anglo-german-naval-arms-race] The first Chancellor of united Germany Otto von Bismarck had skillfully guided Germany's foreign relations so it was not firmly attached to any other European power.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anglo-german-naval-arms-race] After his departure in 1890, Germany's foreign policy drifted into deeper commitment with the Triple Alliance of Austria-Hungary and Italy.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anglo-german-naval-arms-race] Friedrich von Holstein of the German Foreign Office convinced the new Chancellor, Leo von Caprivi, to not renew the Reinsurance Treaty with the Russian Empire in 1890.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anglo-german-naval-arms-race] Bismarck had designed the Reinsurance Treaty to keep Russia from an alliance with France; the Russian search for allies who could finance their enormous debts resulted in the Franco-Russian Alliance several years later.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anglo-german-naval-arms-race] Holstein had hoped that the lapsing of the Reinsurance Treaty would result in a closer relationship with Britain, which was competing with both Russia and France, which did not occur.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anglo-german-naval-arms-race] From 1890 to 1897, Germany wavered between pro-British and pro-Russian policies, reflecting the incoherence of German leadership.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anglo-german-naval-arms-race] In 1890, Alfred Thayer Mahan, an American naval officer and historian, published *The Influence of Sea Power upon History*, widely considered the most important work in modern naval strategy.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anglo-german-naval-arms-race] Mahan argued that sea power was the deciding factor that allowed strong nations to thrive and impose their will on weaker nations, and that the proper way to achieve naval supremacy was large-scale battles between fleets.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anglo-german-naval-arms-race] At the time, the Imperial German Navy subscribed to the commerce raiding theory of navy strategy, but Mahan's arguments had enormous influence over subsequent German and British thinking.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anglo-german-naval-arms-race] Translated into German by Admiral Ludwig Borckenhagen, who supported Mahan's ideas, a copy of the book was placed in every German naval vessel.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anglo-german-naval-arms-race] Kaiser Wilhelm II immediately subscribed to Mahan's ideas after reading his book in 1894 and sought Reichstag funding to implement them.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anglo-german-naval-arms-race] The Reichstag funded four of the thirty-six cruisers that Wilhelm requested in 1895, and none at all the following two years.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anglo-german-naval-arms-race] Frustrated at being rebuffed, Wilhelm recalled von Tirpitz from his duties in the Far East to be the Secretary of State of the German Imperial Naval Office in 1897.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anglo-german-naval-arms-race] Tirpitz was a follower of anti-British nationalist Heinrich von Treitschke as well as Mahan's ideas on the primacy of battle fleets.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anglo-german-naval-arms-race] In 1894, he wrote a famous memorandum section titled, *The Natural Purpose of a Fleet is the Strategic Offensive*, dismissing commerce raiding and coastal defense, and arguing that Germany must prepare for offensive sea battle to ensure its place in the world.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anglo-german-naval-arms-race] In his first meeting with Wilhelm in June 1897, Tirpitz stated his case that Germany must confront Britain to ensure its place as a European power.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anglo-german-naval-arms-race] He also outlined a strategy that he would follow for many years: build a German navy strong enough that the effort to destroy it would open Britain to attack from Britain's French and Russian rivals, which is a form of Mahan's "fleet in being".
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anglo-german-naval-arms-race] Although Britain maintained formal independence from the Triple Alliance, it entered into informal understandings with Italy and Austria-Hungary in the 1887 Mediterranean protocol.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anglo-german-naval-arms-race] These were strategic discussions rather than binding treaties, aimed to check Russian influence and secure access for the Royal Navy.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anglo-german-naval-arms-race] In accord with Wilhelm II's enthusiasm for an expanded German navy and the strategic vision of Tirpitz, five Fleet Acts in 1898, 1900, 1906, 1908, and 1912 greatly expanded the German High Seas Fleet.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anglo-german-naval-arms-race] The German aim was to build a fleet that would be two thirds the size of the British navy.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anglo-german-naval-arms-race] The First Naval Act passed in March 1898 after an extensive lobbying and public relations campaign led by Wilhelm, Tirpitz, and Bülow.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anglo-german-naval-arms-race] The act funded the building of eleven battleships in the next seven years.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anglo-german-naval-arms-race] Britain had little concern about the First Naval Act as it did not increase Germany's navy to a size relevant to the two-power standard.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anglo-german-naval-arms-race] However, by November 1898, Tirpitz had begun work on a plan to double the fleet to include forty-five battleships and armored cruisers, which he presented to the Kaiser in September 1899.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anglo-german-naval-arms-race] The timing was fortunate, as the eruption of the Second Boer War and British seizure of a German steamer off southern Africa enraged the German public against Britain; the Reichstag passed the Second Navy Law in June 1900.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anglo-german-naval-arms-race] The passage of the Second Naval Act in Germany increased worry among British policymakers.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anglo-german-naval-arms-race] In 1902, First Lord of the Admiralty William Palmer, 2nd Earl of Selborne, Tirpitz's British counterpart, told his fellow Cabinet members that the German navy was being built with an eye for war with Britain.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anglo-german-naval-arms-race] Admiral Jacky Fisher was appointed First Sea Lord (professional head of the Royal Navy) in 1904, and massively reorganized the Royal Navy by bringing most of Britain's navy force close to the home isles.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anglo-german-naval-arms-race] He also set up a committee to design a new super battleship, which especially in the wake of the May 1905 Battle of Tsushima seemed to be the future of naval warfare.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anglo-german-naval-arms-race] HMS *Dreadnought* was launched in February 1906, just 14 months after being approved.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anglo-german-naval-arms-race] *Jane's Fighting Ships*, an annual reference book on naval warships, noted that HMS *Dreadnought* was equivalent to two or three normal battleships.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anglo-german-naval-arms-race] In the beginning of 1905, the German naval attaché in Britain reported to Tirpitz that the British were planning a new class of battleship.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anglo-german-naval-arms-race] That summer, Tirpitz consulted with his advisers; by autumn, he had decided that Germany would match the British naval building plan.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anglo-german-naval-arms-race] Scholars highlight that Imperial German decision-making was so incoherent that Tirpitz could make this decision without consulting the Chancellor, foreign ministry, treasury, the naval strategic planning offices, or the two other naval offices: the Naval High Command and Naval Cabinet.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anglo-german-naval-arms-race] He presented his new supplementary naval bill to the Reichstag, envisioning a 35% increase in spending over the Second Naval Act to build two dreadnoughts and one armored cruiser per year.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anglo-german-naval-arms-race] The bill encountered fierce opposition from across the political spectrum because of the growing government budget balance and resistance by the Reichstag to raising taxes.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anglo-german-naval-arms-race] Fortunately for the bill, the Algeciras Conference that concluded in April 1906 after the First Moroccan Crisis inflamed German nationalist sentiment against Britain and France and the third naval law passed easily in May 1906.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anglo-german-naval-arms-race] Wilhelm and Tirpitz, among other German leaders, viewed British actions as working in concert with France and Russia to encircle Germany.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anglo-german-naval-arms-race] Tirpitz believed that the British knew that they had made a mistake in building the expensive dreadnoughts and armored cruisers, and that they would realize their folly if Germany did not flinch in following them.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anglo-german-naval-arms-race] German leaders had also become increasingly nervous about a 'Kopenhagen', a British strike to disable their fleet like that conducted in the 1807 Battle of Copenhagen.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anglo-german-naval-arms-race] In December 1904, during the heightened tensions of the Russo-Japanese War, rumours spread that Japan's ally Britain would attack and the German ambassador to Britain, who was in Berlin, had to reassure Wilhelm and other senior officials that Britain did not intend to start a war.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anglo-german-naval-arms-race] As fears rose, so did nationalist sentiment, including right-wing criticism of the leftist Social Democratic Party, who resisted higher defence spending and encouraged peaceful foreign relations.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anglo-german-naval-arms-race] From 1905 onward, Admiral Fisher developed war plans for blockading the German coast; it became a central British strategy and was implemented in 1914.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anglo-german-naval-arms-race] In 1906, Fisher declared that Germany was the "only probable enemy" and that the Royal Navy should keep a force twice as powerful as Germany's navy within a few hours of Germany's shores.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anglo-german-naval-arms-race] Eyre Crowe of the British Foreign Office wrote a memorandum on 1 January 1907 to Foreign Secretary Sir Edward Grey that became policy.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anglo-german-naval-arms-race] In it, Crowe urged stalwart resistance to what he viewed as Germany's attempts at hegemony in Europe.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anglo-german-naval-arms-race] He argued that German actions might be the result of a confused strategy, but that the intent was irrelevant to British national security.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anglo-german-naval-arms-race] In March 1908, Tirpitz got a fourth naval bill – the second supplementary bill – passed by the Reichstag.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anglo-german-naval-arms-race] It increased the rate of new battleships from three to four per year for the next four years, before stabilizing at three per year.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anglo-german-naval-arms-race] If implemented, Germany would have had 21 dreadnoughts in 1914.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anglo-german-naval-arms-race] The heightened tensions around the Bosnian crisis led Chancellor Bülow, who was responsible for finding the money to fund the military, to question the value of Tirpitz's strategy, which was costly and appeared to increase Germany's diplomatic isolation.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anglo-german-naval-arms-race] Germany's national debt had doubled between 1900 and 1908 and most of the national budget went to the military.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anglo-german-naval-arms-race] Bülow was coming to the conclusion that Germany could not afford both the largest army and second-largest navy in Europe.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anglo-german-naval-arms-race] Though the German ambassador in London, Paul Metternich, reported that the naval buildup was alienating Britain from Germany, Tirpitz stated that the conflict with Germany was based in economic rivalry, not competing navies.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anglo-german-naval-arms-race] Tirpitz also argued that Germany had invested too much money into the naval program to halt it and that the domestic political coalition that had been created to support the naval buildup would react unpredictably if the government left the arms race.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anglo-german-naval-arms-race] Facing an ever-expanding budget deficit, but lacking the confidence of the Kaiser and unable to raise taxes in the face of Reichstag opposition, Bülow resigned in July 1909.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anglo-german-naval-arms-race] Up to Germany's 1908 naval bill, Britain in general had largely ignored the buildup, though some individuals in the military and government were already keenly aware of the potential threat.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anglo-german-naval-arms-race] However, in the summer following the 1908 bill, alarm among the public and in the government rose.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anglo-german-naval-arms-race] In August 1908, King Edward VII visited his nephew Wilhelm in Kronberg.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anglo-german-naval-arms-race] He had been provided with a paper outlining British concerns but decided not to raise the issue of naval spending, as it might spoil the congenial mood.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anglo-german-naval-arms-race] Wilhelm cheerfully commented to Permanent Under-Secretary of State for Foreign Affairs Charles Hardinge that he thought relations between Germany and Britain were quite good.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anglo-german-naval-arms-race] Hardinge politely disagreed, stating that British concern at the German naval buildup would likely result in the Liberal government asking Parliament to expand British naval shipbuilding, resulting in a naval rivalry that would greatly increase tensions between the two countries.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anglo-german-naval-arms-race] Wilhelm sharply replied that there was no reason for British concern, and that the German naval bill did not threaten the relative strengths of the two navies.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anglo-german-naval-arms-race] No resolution was reached, and Wilhelm left the Kronberg meeting believing that he had convinced the British of the justness of Germany's position.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anglo-german-naval-arms-race] A series of incidents escalated British tension.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anglo-german-naval-arms-race] In autumn 1908, the British naval attaché in Berlin reported that Germany was building an extra battleship; in reality, ship builder Schichau-Werke had asked the government for an early contract to build a ship scheduled for 1909 to avoid laying off workers in Danzig (now: Gdańsk, Poland).
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anglo-german-naval-arms-race] Then on 28 October, *The Daily Telegraph* published what was described as an interview with the Kaiser.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anglo-german-naval-arms-race] The *Telegraph* sent the piece to Wilhelm for approval, who in turn passed it to Chancellor Bülow, who passed it on to the Foreign Ministry for their review, which apparently did not take place.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anglo-german-naval-arms-race] The Daily Telegraph Affair was variously seen in Britain as evidence that Wilhelm was mentally unbalanced or that it was part of a sinister plan to sway British public opinion.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anglo-german-naval-arms-race] German leaders were appalled that their leader would make such a public fool of himself, nationalists and conservatives were infuriated by Wilhelm's declarations of friendship with Britain, and leftists were convinced that the Reichstag needed more control over the Kaiser.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anglo-german-naval-arms-race] Wilhelm and the throne were severely weakened, and the Kaiser fell into a dark depression.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anglo-german-naval-arms-race] Wilhelm never forgave Bülow for allowing the publication, which was a contributing factor in the Chancellor's departure in July 1909.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anglo-german-naval-arms-race] After the German bill, the Admiralty abandoned its plan for reduced construction and, in December 1908, proposed building at least six more dreadnoughts.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anglo-german-naval-arms-race] Opposition in the Cabinet revolved around the cost, led by Chancellor of the Exchequer David Lloyd George and President of the Board of Trade Winston Churchill, who both saw the military expenditures as threats to the welfare reforms promised by the Liberal Party.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anglo-german-naval-arms-race] Lloyd George warned Prime Minister Asquith that Liberal MPs would revolt at a proposal adding an estimated £38 million in naval expenditures to the budget.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anglo-german-naval-arms-race] However, the Conservative opposition, the Navy League, and British arms industry advocated for the spending.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anglo-german-naval-arms-race] In popular sentiment, they were joined by King Edward VII, who supported eight more dreadnoughts.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anglo-german-naval-arms-race] In response to the broad support for increased naval strength, Asquith arranged a compromise in February 1909 to start four dreadnoughts in the next financial year, with an additional four more by spring 1910 if they were needed.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anglo-german-naval-arms-race] With the Liberals in support, the government defeated a motion of no confidence brought by the Conservatives.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anglo-german-naval-arms-race] Lloyd George included the additional dreadnoughts in his proposed "People's Budget" at the end of April 1909, which was rejected in November 1909 by the House of Lords, who were outraged by the measures to redistribute wealth.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anglo-german-naval-arms-race] Asquith dissolved Parliament to hold an election in January 1910; his government lost its majority but remained in office with the support of the Irish Parliamentary Party.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anglo-german-naval-arms-race] In the wake of the election, the House of Lords dropped its opposition to the People's Budget, including funding for the dreadnoughts, which passed in April 1910 and was a significant escalation of the arms race.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anglo-german-naval-arms-race] In 1912, German Chancellor Theobald von Bethmann Hollweg tried to end the naval arms race.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anglo-german-naval-arms-race] His aim was to secure an understanding with the British to end the increasingly isolated position of Germany.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anglo-german-naval-arms-race] Russian military expansion compelled the Germans to prioritise spending on their army and therefore less on the navy, a policy known as the *Rüstungswende* or ‘armaments turning point'.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anglo-german-naval-arms-race] The initiative led to the Haldane Mission in which Germany offered to accept British naval superiority in exchange for British neutrality in a war in which Germany could not be said to be the aggressor.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anglo-german-naval-arms-race] The proposal was rejected, as Britain felt that it had nothing to gain by such a treaty since its naval superiority was secure, but the British Foreign Secretary Sir Edward Grey favoured a more assertive policy against Germany.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anglo-german-naval-arms-race] By 1913, there was intense internal debate in Britain about new ships because of the growing influence of Fisher's ideas and increasing financial constraints.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anglo-german-naval-arms-race] It is now generally accepted by historians that in the first half of 1914, the Germans adopted a policy of building submarines instead of new dreadnoughts and destroyers, effectively abandoning the arms race, but since they kept the new policy secret, other powers would be delayed in following suit.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anglo-german-naval-arms-race] By the start of the First World War, Britain had 20 commissioned dreadnoughts and 9 battlecruisers, compared with Germany's 15 commissioned dreadnoughts and 7 battlecruisers.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anti-tank-gun] An **anti-tank gun** is a form of artillery designed to destroy tanks and other armored fighting vehicles, normally from a static defensive position.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anti-tank-gun] The development of specialized anti-tank munitions and anti-tank guns was prompted by the appearance of tanks during World War I.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anti-tank-gun] To destroy hostile tanks, artillerymen often used field guns depressed to fire directly at their targets, but this practice expended too much valuable ammunition and was of increasingly limited effectiveness as tank armor became thicker.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anti-tank-gun] The first dedicated anti-tank artillery began appearing in the 1920s, and by World War II was a common appearance in many European armies.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anti-tank-gun] To penetrate armor, they fired specialized ammunition from longer barrels to achieve a higher muzzle velocity than field guns.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anti-tank-gun] Most anti-tank guns were developed in the 1930s as improvements in tanks were noted, and nearly every major arms manufacturer produced one type or another.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anti-tank-gun] Anti-tank guns deployed during World War II were often manned by specialist infantry rather than artillery crews, and issued to light infantry units accordingly.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anti-tank-gun] The anti-tank guns of the 1920s and 1930s were of small caliber; nearly all major armies possessing them used 37 mm ammunition (the British Army used the slightly larger 40 mm 2-pounder gun).
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anti-tank-gun] As World War II progressed, the appearance of heavier tanks rendered these weapons obsolete, and anti-tank guns likewise began firing larger and more effective armor-piercing shots.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anti-tank-gun] Although several large-caliber guns were developed during the war that could knock out the most heavily armored tanks, they proved expensive and difficult to conceal.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anti-tank-gun] The later generation of low-recoil anti-tank weapons, which allowed projectiles the size of an artillery shell to be fired from the shoulder, was considered a far more viable option for arming infantry.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anti-tank-gun] Recoilless rifles replaced most conventional anti-tank guns in the postwar period; nevertheless, the development of new anti-tank guns exhibiting similar low-recoil performance continued until the late 1950s in France, Belgium, and the Soviet Union.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anti-tank-gun] A few Soviet designs saw combat well into the 1980s and 1990s.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anti-tank-gun] The first specialized anti-tank weaponry consisted of anti-tank rifles.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anti-tank-gun] These emerged from the mixed results of deploying field artillery against tanks during World War I, and the need to produce a more economical weapon to destroy them.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anti-tank-gun] Most anti-tank rifles were over 1.3 m (4 ft 3 in) in length, however, and difficult for soldiers to operate in the confines of their trenches.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anti-tank-gun] They could penetrate a tank's armor at long range, but without explosive firepower, often failed to cause catastrophic damage, kill, or even seriously injure the crew, or disable the tank.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anti-tank-gun] Many infantry support guns designed to defeat hard targets such as fortified machine gun emplacements were used as makeshift anti-tank weapons, including the French Canon d'Infanterie de 37 modèle 1916 TRP.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anti-tank-gun] The 3.7 cm Tankabwehrkanone 1918 im starrer Räder–lafette was probably the first dedicated anti-tank gun in service.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anti-tank-gun] However, its gun barrel was based on an earlier Hotchkiss 5-barrelled rotary-cannon.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anti-tank-gun] The 3.7 cm TAK 1918 was designed and built for the Imperial German Army in 1918.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anti-tank-gun] The 3.7 cm Pak 36 which first appeared in 1928 was probably the first purpose-built anti-tank gun.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anti-tank-gun] Weighing some 160 kg (350 lb), the Pak 36 could inflict a catastrophic kill on a tank rather than merely penetrating its armor plate.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anti-tank-gun] Towed guns similar to the Pak 36 were the only anti-tank weapon issued to European armies during the 1930s, and several influential designs proliferated, such as the Böhler gun.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anti-tank-gun] By the late 1930s, anti-tank guns had been manufactured by companies in Germany, Austria, France, Czechoslovakia, Belgium, Great Britain, Denmark, and Sweden.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anti-tank-gun] A few countries, such as the Soviet Union, also manufactured foreign designs under license.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anti-tank-gun] At the outbreak of World War II, most armies were fielding light anti-tank guns firing 37 mm ammunition.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anti-tank-gun] The guns were usually mounted on two-wheeled carriages so they could be towed into position, then withdrawn and repositioned rapidly.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anti-tank-gun] Since they weighed only a few hundred pounds on average, they could also be shoved into position.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anti-tank-gun] All fired high-explosive and solid armor-piercing shot effective at ranges up to roughly 500 m (1,600 ft), and an increasing number were manufactured with protective gun shields in addition to a split rail mounting.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anti-tank-gun] They were able to destroy tanks fielded by both sides during the first two years of the war, but soon proved impotent against the heavier tank armor that debuted in 1940.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anti-tank-gun] French doctrine was for their infantry to let enemy tanks pass through, then stop the accompanying enemy infantry, leaving the unsupported tanks to be engaged by anti-tank guns deployed in three echelons.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anti-tank-gun] The issue of 58 guns per division provided 10 guns per kilometer of front, which was expected to be sufficient to deal with an enemy tank concentration of 50 tanks per kilometer.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anti-tank-gun] In practice, the German invasion of France concentrated tanks in select divisions at up to 100 per kilometer.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anti-tank-gun] Introducing improved ammunition and increasing muzzle velocity initially helped compensate for their mediocre performance, but small-caliber anti-tank guns clearly would soon be overtaken by yet more heavily armored tanks.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anti-tank-gun] Medium-caliber guns in the 40- to 50-mm range began to appear, some of which used rebored 37-mm barrels.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anti-tank-gun] Although they, too, were soon approaching obsolescence, most remained in use with infantry units until the end of the war.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anti-tank-gun] Anti-tank guns remained ineffective against sloped armor, as demonstrated by an incident in 1941 when a single Soviet T-34 tank was hit more than 30 times by a battalion-sized contingent of German 37 and 50-mm anti-tank guns.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anti-tank-gun] The tank survived intact and was driven back to its own lines a few hours later.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anti-tank-gun] This helped earn the Pak 36 the moniker of *Panzeranklopfgerät* ("tank door knocker") because its crew revealed their presence and wasted their shells without damaging the T-34's armor.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anti-tank-gun] Anti-tank gunners began aiming at tank tracks, or vulnerable margins on the turret ring and gun mantlet, rather than testing their lighter cannon against bow and turret armor.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anti-tank-gun] These difficulties resulted in new types of ammunition being issued, namely high-explosive anti-tank (HEAT) and armor-piercing discarding sabot (APDS) projectiles.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anti-tank-gun] Towards the end of World War II, armor plating became still thicker, with tanks such as the Tiger II being fitted with armor over 100 mm (3.9 in) in thickness, as compared to 15 mm (0.59 in), which was more typical in 1939.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anti-tank-gun] This prompted the development of a third generation of anti-tank guns, large-caliber pieces in the 57- to 100-mm range.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anti-tank-gun] The British Army adopted the Ordnance QF 6-pounder and Ordnance QF 17-pounder, which were then considered great advances in firepower, and the Wehrmacht fielded the even larger 7.5 cm Pak 41 and 8.8 cm Pak 43.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anti-tank-gun] While the early 37-mm anti-tank guns were easily concealed and moved, the large-caliber weapons available late in the war required equally large vehicles to tow them into place, and were difficult to conceal, dig in, withdraw, or reposition.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anti-tank-gun] By 1945, large anti-tank guns had become almost impractical in their role, and their size and weight were considered liabilities.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anti-tank-gun] They were also expensive to produce, and although they were capable of defeating the most formidable of opponents, most tank units still consisted of less heavily armored models that remained vulnerable to less expensive and more practical guns, as well.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anti-tank-gun] Many heavy anti-tank guns were issued, at least initially, on the divisional level, but gradually made their way to individual infantry battalions.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anti-tank-gun] Meanwhile, the effect of very compact hollow charge warheads was being noted, and several countries began producing man-portable anti-tank weapons using this ammunition.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anti-tank-gun] The development of man-portable, shoulder-fired, anti-tank rocket launchers began in 1941; most could be reloaded, but a few, such as the German Panzerfaust, were fired from disposable tubes.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anti-tank-gun] Unlike anti-tank guns, their lightweight design made them easily portable by individual soldiers on the battlefield, and they offered comparable firepower whilst being quicker and cheaper to produce.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anti-tank-gun] Towed anti-tank guns disappeared from most Western countries, such as the United States, after World War II, to be replaced by shoulder-fired rocket launchers, recoilless rifles, and eventually, guided anti-tank missiles.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anti-tank-gun] At the end of the war, German engineers had proposed a new, large-caliber anti-tank gun that used less propellant than a rocket or a recoilless weapon, yet fired compact, hollow-charge shells similar to those used by the latter.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anti-tank-gun] German forces subsequently fielded the 8 cm PAW 600, which was an extremely lightweight, low-pressure weapon still able to fire the same ammunition types as higher-velocity anti-tank guns.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anti-tank-gun] In the 1950s, this idea was revived by a Belgian firm, Mecar, which subsequently improved on the concept and developed a low-pressure, smoothbore, 90-mm anti-tank gun.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anti-tank-gun] Because of its low recoil forces and light construction, the gun was particularly useful for being mounted on armored cars or small gun carriages.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anti-tank-gun] Its design inspired the lightly rifled French DEFA D921 anti-tank gun, which fired fin-stabilized shells and was available on a towed carriage or as a vehicle mount.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anti-tank-gun] It was later mated to the AML-90 and EBR series of French armored cars.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anti-tank-gun] The Soviet Union also adopted a similar design around the same time, the 100-mm T-12 anti-tank gun, which was smoothbore and fired fin-stabilized shells.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anti-tank-gun] Switzerland developed a postwar 90-mm anti-tank gun of its own, the Pak 50/57, firing shells with an even lower velocity than the Mecar or DEFA guns.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anti-tank-gun] Apart from the T-12, which used APDS rounds, these weapons could only use HEAT shells for armor-piercing purposes.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anti-tank-gun] France did introduce an APFSDS shell for the DEFA D921 at some point in the 1980s.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anti-tank-gun] The last country known to have produced a dedicated anti-tank gun was the People's Republic of China in 1988.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anti-tank-gun] The Chinese gun was known as the Norinco Type 86 and was probably manufactured as a replacement for the aging Soviet-sourced T-12.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anti-tank-gun] Anti-tank guns continued to be used in many conflicts around the world, such as the Six-Day War and the South African Border War.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anti-tank-gun] Soviet anti-tank guns in particular were exported to at least 18 other countries after being retired from service, and have continued to see action.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anti-tank-gun] Although still being drawn by horses or towed by trucks, towed anti-tank guns were initially much lighter and more portable than field guns, making them well-suited to infantry maneuvers.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anti-tank-gun] As their size and caliber increased, though, the guns likewise became increasingly heavy and cumbersome, restricting their role to static defense.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anti-tank-gun] Consequently, during World War II, both sides were compelled to make anti-tank guns self-propelled, greatly increasing their mobility.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anti-tank-gun] Although just a makeshift solution, these initial experiments proved so successful that they spawned an entire class of new vehicles: dedicated tank destroyers.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anti-tank-gun] The US Army's early self-propelled anti-tank guns were 75 mm on M2 half-tracks (entering service in 1941) to complement towed artillery and M6 gun motor carriage, a 37 mm on a 4-wheel-drive Dodge truck (1942).
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anti-tank-gun] US tank destroyer doctrine emphasized mobility to position tank destroyers for ambushes against tank attacks.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anti-tank-gun] The introduction of tank destroyers also put an end to the traditional tactic of suppressing anti-tank gun batteries with heavy artillery bombardments, as their crews were now well-protected under armor.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anti-tank-gun] They were not without their own series of disadvantages, however, namely presenting a much larger target than a towed gun, the added responsibilities of vehicle maintenance and logistical support, and the limited spaces in which the crew had to operate and stow all their available ammunition.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anti-tank-gun] By the end of the war, dedicated tank destroyers had been superseded by tanks, which were just as effective at destroying other tanks, and little incentive remained to continue their separate development.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/anti-tank-gun] Nevertheless, much like towed anti-tank guns, they were widely exported and are still in service with some militaries in the late 20th and early 21st century.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/arms-race] An arms race is a competition between two or more states to have superior armed forces, concerning production of weapons, the growth of a military, and the aim of superior military technology.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/arms-race] Unlike a sporting race, which constitutes a specific event with winning interpretable as the outcome of a singular project, arms races constitute spiralling systems of on-going and potentially open-ended behavior.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/arms-race] The existing scholarly literature is divided as to whether arms races correlate with war.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/arms-race] International-relations scholars explain arms races in terms of the security dilemma, engineering spiral models, states with revisionist aims, and deterrence models.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/arms-race] From 1897 to 1914, a naval arms race between the United Kingdom and Germany took place.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/arms-race] British concern about rapid increase in German naval power resulted in a costly building competition of *Dreadnought*-class ships.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/arms-race] This tense arms race lasted until 1914, when the war broke out.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/arms-race] After the war, a new arms race developed among the victorious Allies, which was temporarily ended by the Washington Naval Treaty.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/arms-race] In addition to the British and Germans, contemporaneous but smaller naval arms races also broke out between Russia and the Ottoman Empire; the Ottomans and Greece; France and Italy; the United States and Japan in the 1930s; and Brazil, Argentina, and Chile.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/arms-race] This contest of the advancement of offensive nuclear capabilities occurred during the Cold War, an intense period between the Soviet Union and the United States and some other countries.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/arms-race] This was one of the main causes that began the Cold War, and perceived advantages of the adversary by both sides (such as the missile gap and bomber gap) led to large spending on armaments and the stockpiling of vast nuclear arsenals.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/arms-race] Proxy wars were fought all over the world (e.g. in the Middle East, Korea, and Vietnam) in which the superpowers' conventional weapons were pitted against each other.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/arms-race] After the dissolution of the Soviet Union and the end of the Cold War, tensions decreased and the nuclear arsenal of both countries were reduced.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/arms-race] Charles Glaser argues that numerous cases of arms races were suboptimal, as they entailed a waste of resources, damaged political relations, increased the probability of war, and hindered states in accomplishing their goals.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/arms-race] However, arms races can be optimal for security-seeking states in situations when the offense-defense balance favors offense, when a declining state faces a rising adversary, and when advances in technology make existing weapons obsolete for the power that had an advantage in the existing weaponry.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/arms-race] A military **artificial intelligence arms race** is an arms race between two or more states to develop and deploy lethal autonomous weapons systems (LAWS).
[src:rifled-breech-loader/arms-race] Since the mid-2010s, many analysts have noted the emergence of such an arms race between global superpowers for better military AI, driven by increasing geopolitical and military tensions.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/arms-race] An AI arms race is sometimes placed in the context of an AI Cold War between the US and China.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/arms-race] An evolutionary arms race is a system where two populations are evolving in order to continuously one-up members of the other population.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/arms-race] This concept is related to the Red Queen's Hypothesis, where two opposing organisms evolve in parralell to overcome each other but both fail to progress relative to the other.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/arms-race] In technology, there are close analogues to the arms races between parasites and hosts, such as the arms race between writers of computer viruses and antivirus software, or spammers against Internet service providers and E-mail software writers.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/arms-race] More generically, the term is used to describe any competition where there is no absolute goal, only the relative goal of staying ahead of the other competitors in rank or knowledge.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/arms-race] An arms race may also imply futility as the competitors spend a great deal of time and money, yet with neither side gaining an advantage over the other.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/armstrong-gun] An **Armstrong gun** was a type of rifled breech-loading field and heavy artillery piece designed by Sir William Armstrong.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/armstrong-gun] It was first manufactured in England starting in 1855 by the Elswick Ordnance Company and the Royal Arsenal at Woolwich.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/armstrong-gun] The Armstrong gun employed a distinctive built-up gun construction method.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/armstrong-gun] The core of the gun consisted of a wrought iron (and later, mild steel) inner tube, which was reinforced by a series of wrought-iron coils shrunk over it.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/armstrong-gun] This design kept the inner tube under constant compression, increasing its strength and resistance to internal pressure generated during firing.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/armstrong-gun] In 1854, Armstrong approached the Secretary of State for War with a proposal to construct a rifled breech-loading 3-pounder gun for evaluation.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/armstrong-gun] The gun was later modified to a 5-pounder, and the design proved successful in terms of both range and accuracy.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/armstrong-gun] Over the next three years, Armstrong further developed his system of construction and adapted it to guns of larger calibres.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/armstrong-gun] Although Armstrong did not consider his system suitable for heavier guns, the government directed him to develop larger calibres, including the 20-pounder/9.1 kg (3.75 in/95 mm) field and naval gun, the 40-pounder/18 kg (4.75 in/121 mm) siege gun, and the 110-pounder/50 kg (7 in/180 mm) heavy gun.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/armstrong-gun] The Royal Navy adopted all three guns, and all except the 20-pounder saw service in New Zealand.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/armstrong-gun] Armstrong’s guns used a “built-up” construction, comprising a central “A” tube—initially made of wrought iron, and from 1863 onwards of mild steel toughened by oil treatment—forming the bore.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/armstrong-gun] Over this tube were shrunk several wrought-iron coils which kept the central tube under compression, along with a breech-piece and a trunnion ring.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/armstrong-gun] The guns employed a “polygroove” rifling system: the bore had 38 grooves along its length, with a twist rate of one complete turn per 38 calibres.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/armstrong-gun] The cast iron shell, shaped similarly to a Minié ball, had a thin lead coating making it slightly larger than the bore diameter; this coating engaged with the rifling grooves to impart spin.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/armstrong-gun] This system was originally developed by Martin von Wahrendorff and Giovanni Cavalli in Sweden.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/armstrong-gun] The spin stabilization, combined with the elimination of windage due to the tight fit, allowed the gun to achieve greater range and accuracy than contemporary smoothbore muzzle-loaders while using a smaller powder charge.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/armstrong-gun] Each gunpowder cartridge was topped with a “lubricator” composed of a mixture of tallow and linseed oil contained between two tin plates, backed by a felt wad coated with beeswax, and finally sealed with millboard.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/armstrong-gun] The lubricator followed the shell down the bore; the lubricant was squeezed out between the tin plates, while the wad cleaned lead deposits left by the shell’s coating, leaving the bore clean for subsequent rounds.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/armstrong-gun] A particularly innovative feature, more commonly associated with 20th-century artillery, was Armstrong’s “grip”: a slight reduction in diameter over the last 6 inches (150 mm) of the bore at the muzzle end, effectively a squeeze bore.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/armstrong-gun] This section centred the shell before leaving the barrel and swaged down its lead coating slightly, reducing its diameter and improving ballistic performance.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/armstrong-gun] The Armstrong breech loaders used a vertical sliding block called a vent-piece, which had a conical copper-ringed plug on its front surface to seal the firing chamber and close the breech.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/armstrong-gun] The British used Armstrong guns extensively and with great effect during the Second Opium War.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/armstrong-gun] The Armstrong gun—primarily the 12-pounder—was used extensively during the 1863 conflict in New Zealand between British troops and Māori in the Waikato.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/armstrong-gun] A well-preserved 12-pounder/5.4 kg used at the Battle of Rangiriri is displayed at the Te Awamutu Museum.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/armstrong-gun] The barrel could traverse 6 degrees left or right without moving the gun carriage.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/armstrong-gun] The wheels were wooden with 75 mm wide steel bands, with a diameter of 1.7 m.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/armstrong-gun] The track width was 1.8 m, and the barrel width at the muzzle measured 140 mm.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/armstrong-gun] Such was the army’s confidence in the gun’s accuracy that, at the Battle of Hairini Ridge, the artillery fired over the heads of advancing infantry as they stormed the ridge.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/armstrong-gun] The infantry took cover in a slight depression in the ground in front of the Māori trenches and then charged the trenches once the shelling ceased.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/armstrong-gun] On 4 July 1868, Armstrong guns were used at the Battle of Ueno by forces supporting the Imperial government of Japan.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/armstrong-gun] Armstrong guns were also used against British and Indian troops during the Second Anglo-Afghan War, notably at the Battle of Charasiab.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/armstrong-gun] Howard Hensman describes six guns being captured by a combined Anglo-Indian expedition under the command of Brigadier-General Baker.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/armstrong-gun] In 1863, an ordnance Select Committee was convened to assess the relative merits of muzzle-loading and breech-loading guns.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/armstrong-gun] In 1864, even before the committee had concluded its investigation, the British Government halted the manufacture of Armstrong breech-loaders.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/armstrong-gun] However, the report also acknowledged that while Armstrong guns were more costly, they were undoubtedly safer.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/armstrong-gun] It was not uncommon for cast-iron muzzle-loaders to burst during firing, but no Armstrong gun had ever done so.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/armstrong-gun] Moreover, misfires could be safely cleared from the breech in Armstrong designs.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/armstrong-gun] In contrast, a misfire in a muzzle-loader—such as the RML 17.72 inches (450 mm) gun at the Napier of Magdala Battery in Gibraltar—required extreme measures; in one instance, a gunner had to be lowered head-first down the bore to attach an extractor to the shell.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/armstrong-gun] Smaller muzzle-loading guns, however, were typically equipped with standard extraction tools.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/armstrong-gun] Despite a subsequent report that highlighted the advantages of breech-loaders, cost considerations prevailed.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/armstrong-gun] The Committee ultimately concluded that "the balance of advantages is in favour of muzzle-loading field guns," and in 1865 Britain officially reverted from breech-loading ordnance to muzzle-loading systems.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/armstrong-gun] Tests conducted in 1859 with the Armstrong 40-pounder/18 kg, and again in 1869 with the Armstrong rifled 100-pounder/45 kg, demonstrated that neither gun was capable of penetrating 4 inches (100 mm) of armour, even at ranges as close as 50 yards (46 m).
[src:rifled-breech-loader/armstrong-gun] This limitation was significant, as Britain, a dominant maritime power, relied heavily on the ability of its naval ordnance to penetrate the armour of newly developed enemy warships.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/armstrong-gun] In an effort to address the shortcomings of his original screw breech mechanism, Armstrong developed an alternative horizontal sliding wedge breech system for 40-pounder/18 kg and 64-pounder/29 kg guns.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/armstrong-gun] However, by that time, the Government had already committed to reverting to muzzle-loading artillery.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/armstrong-gun] To enable rifling in muzzle-loaders, Armstrong proposed a new system in 1866 whereby shells were equipped with external studs that engaged with corresponding grooves in the barrel.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/armstrong-gun] This system was adopted by the Government for the first generation of rifled muzzle-loaders, designated "RML," and incorporated Armstrong’s built-up wrought-iron construction method, which was considered sound and reliable.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/armstrong-gun] Armstrong returned to the manufacture of breech-loading guns in the 1880s, employing an interrupted thread breech mechanism that incorporated the proprietary "Armstrong cup" and later adopted the de Bange system of obturation.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/armstrong-gun] Unlike the earlier 1858 design, which relied on manual effort to create a gas seal, these newer methods used the explosive force of the gun’s firing to achieve obturation more effectively.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/armstrong-gun] During this period, Armstrong became a major supplier of modern "BL" (breech-loading) guns to the Royal Navy, the British Army, and the international export market, continuing into the 1920s.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/rifled-breech-loader] A **rifled breech loader** (RBL) is an artillery piece which, unlike the smoothbore cannon and rifled muzzle loader which preceded it, has rifling in the barrel and is loaded from the breech at the rear of the gun.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/rifled-breech-loader] The spin imparted by the gun's rifling gives projectiles directional stability and increased range.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/rifled-breech-loader] Loading from the rear of the gun leaves the crew less exposed to enemy fire, allows smaller gun emplacements or turrets, and allows a faster rate of fire.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/rifled-breech-loader] These rapidly improving breech systems and the powerful new guns they facilitated led to an arms race in fortification and ironclad warship design that led to the battleship class of HMS *Dreadnought* and continued until the start of World War I.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/rifled-breech-loader] The major problem to be solved with breechloading artillery was obturation: the sealing of the breech after firing to ensure that none of the gases generated by the burning of the propellant (initially gunpowder) escaped rearwards through the breech.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/rifled-breech-loader] This was both a safety issue and one of gun performance – all the propellant gas was needed to accelerate the projectile along the barrel.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/rifled-breech-loader] The second problem was speed of operation – how to close the breech before firing and open it after firing as quickly as possible consistent with safety.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/rifled-breech-loader] Two solutions were developed more or less in parallel, the "screw breech" block and "sliding wedge" or "sliding block".
[src:rifled-breech-loader/rifled-breech-loader] At the time of development of the first modern breechloaders in the mid-19th century, gunpowder propellant charges for artillery were typically loaded in cloth bags, which combusted totally on firing.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/rifled-breech-loader] Hence, unlike with a metal rifle cartridge, the breech mechanism itself somehow needed to provide obturation.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/rifled-breech-loader] The early "screw" mechanisms for sealing the breech consisted of threaded blocks which were screwed tightly into the breech after loading, but the threads themselves were insufficient to provide a gas-tight seal.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/rifled-breech-loader] Hence if the block circumference was divided into two sets of threads and gaps, the block only needed to be rotated ¼ turn to lock it instead of several turns.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/rifled-breech-loader] The tradeoff was that only ½ the block's circumference was threaded, reducing the security accordingly.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/rifled-breech-loader] The other possibility of sealing the breech was to enclose the propellant charge in a metal cartridge case which expanded on firing and hence sealed the breech, leaving the breech-block merely needing to lock the cartridge case in place.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/rifled-breech-loader] This was more easily accomplished by sliding the block in behind the cartridge case through a vertical or horizontal slot cut through the rear of the breech : the "sliding wedge" or "sliding block" breech.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/rifled-breech-loader] The very first cannons of the Middle Ages were breech loaded, with gunpowder and shot contained in pots dropped at the back of the barrel, but the poor seals made them dangerous, and they wore quickly and could not be scaled to larger weapons.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/rifled-breech-loader] Until the 19th century, mainly muzzle-loaders were used.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/rifled-breech-loader] In 1837, Martin von Wahrendorff patented a design for a breech-loader with a cylindrical breech plug secured by a horizontal wedge; it was adopted by Sweden in 1854.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/rifled-breech-loader] Independently, Giovanni Cavalli first proposed a breech-loader gun in 1832 to the Sardinian Army, and first tested such a gun in 1845.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/rifled-breech-loader] Advances in metallurgy in the industrial era allowed for the construction of rifled breech-loading guns that could fire at a much greater muzzle velocity.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/rifled-breech-loader] After the British artillery was shown up in the Crimean War as having barely changed since the Napoleonic Wars the industrialist William Armstrong was awarded a contract by the government to design a new piece of artillery.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/rifled-breech-loader] Production started in 1855 at the Elswick Ordnance Company and the Royal Arsenal at Woolwich.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/rifled-breech-loader] His "Armstrong screw" breech involved loading the shell and gunpowder propellant charge in a cloth bag through the hollow breech screw, lowering a heavy block into a slot behind the powder chamber and screwing the breech screw tightly against the block to lock it in place.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/rifled-breech-loader] A degree of obturation was achieved via a cup on the face of the block being forced into a recessed ring on the chamber face.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/rifled-breech-loader] The system was in effect a vertical sliding block such as later used by Krupp in both horizontal and vertical form, with the crucial difference that Armstrong failed to make the progression to loading the powder charge in a metal cartridge, with the result that complete obturation was impossible.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/rifled-breech-loader] Whatever obturation that was achieved relied on manual labour rather than the power of the gun's firing, and was hence both uncertain, based on an unsound principle and unsuited to large guns.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/rifled-breech-loader] The Imperial Japanese Army used Armstrong cannon during the Boshin War to devastate the Aizu castle town and force its inhabitants to surrender quickly, and British Armstrong light field guns proved deadly against Chinese forces in the Second Opium War.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/rifled-breech-loader] However, the British Army and Navy preferred to revert to muzzle-loaders until larger high-powered breech-loaders with secure obturation systems that were relatively simple to operate were developed.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/rifled-breech-loader] In the meantime the French persevered with trying to develop breechloaders which combined faster loading than muzzle-loaders, high power, safety and solved the problem of obturation.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/rifled-breech-loader] The Lahitolle 95 mm cannon of 1875 with an interrupted screw breech met the first three requirements to a great extent and partially solved the obturation problem.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/rifled-breech-loader] Finally the de Bange system introduced in 1877 solved the obturation problem with an asbestos pad impregnated with grease which expanded and sealed the breech on firing.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/rifled-breech-loader] The de Bange system formed the obturation system for all subsequent screw breeches to the present day.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/rifled-breech-loader] Britain adopted the de Bange breech when it returned to breechloaders in the early 1880s after some initial experiments with the inferior "Armstrong cup" obturation system.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/rifled-breech-loader] Loading required the 3 operations in reverse.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/rifled-breech-loader] This was hence termed a "three motion block" and was slow to operate.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/rifled-breech-loader] While working as a weapons designer for Thorsten Nordenfelt in London, Axel Welin solved this problem in 1889–1890 with his stepped interrupted screw Welin breech block.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/rifled-breech-loader] This allowed the block to be unscrewed and swung out in two motions – the "two motion interrupted screw" breech.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/rifled-breech-loader] Also in the early 1890s, Arent Silfversparre of Bofors invented an ogival screw breech, similar to the Armstrong model in the way it eliminated the need to withdraw the screw before swinging it to the side.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/rifled-breech-loader] Bofors continued to use this in medium artillery into the 20th century.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/rifled-breech-loader] The Elswick conical screw breech is very similar in concept.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/rifled-breech-loader] The German company Krupp in contrast, adopted "Horizontal sliding block" breeches, rather than screw breeches, for all artillery calibres up to 16 in (410 mm) naval guns.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/rifled-breech-loader] This was similar in some ways to the original "Armstrong screw"; the shot and powder cartridge were inserted through the open rear end of the breech into the gun bore, and a steel block was slid home into a horizontal slot cut through the breech to close the rear end of the breech.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/rifled-breech-loader] However, unlike Armstrong, Krupp loaded the powder propellant in a metal cartridge case much like a large rifle cartridge, which expanded against the chamber wall on firing and effectively sealed the breech.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/rifled-breech-loader] The sliding block, in both horizontal and vertical forms, and metal cartridge case continued to be the preferred German breech system until after World War II (e.g.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/rifled-breech-loader] 7.5 cm Pak 40), and is still used by some modern artillery.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/rifled-breech-loader] The first quick-firing light gun was the 1-inch Nordenfelt gun, built in Britain from 1880.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/rifled-breech-loader] The gun was expressly designed to defend larger warships against the new small fast-moving torpedo boats in the late 1870s to the early 1880s and was an enlarged version of the successful rifle-calibre Nordenfelt hand-cranked "machine gun" designed by Helge Palmcrantz.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/rifled-breech-loader] The gun fired a solid steel bullet with hardened tip and brass jacket.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/rifled-breech-loader] It was superseded for anti-torpedo boat defence in the mid-1880s by the new generation of Hotchkiss and Nordenfelt "QF" guns of 47-mm and 57-mm calibre firing exploding "common pointed" shells weighing 3–6 lb (1.4–2.7 kg).
[src:rifled-breech-loader/rifled-breech-loader] The French firm Hotchkiss produced the QF 3 pounder as a light 47-mm naval gun from 1886.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/rifled-breech-loader] The gun was ideal for defending against small fast vessels such as torpedo boats and was immediately adopted by the RN as the "Ordnance QF 3 pounder Hotchkiss".
[src:rifled-breech-loader/rifled-breech-loader] It was built under licence by Elswick Ordnance Company.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/rifled-breech-loader] Both the Hotchkiss and Nordenfelt guns loaded ammunition as a single cartridge with projectile, cartridge case and primer in a single unit.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/rifled-breech-loader] The cartridge case sealed the breech on firing and a vertical sliding wedge (block) locked it in place.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/rifled-breech-loader] These new guns incorporated recoil control devices which facilitated consistency of aim, allowed single-motion loading and could be fired as soon as the cartridge was inserted, and then ejected it after firing, these properties denoting a "quick-firing" gun.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/rifled-breech-loader] This set a new standard for artillery, and made firing cycles measured in seconds rather than minutes possible.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/rifled-breech-loader] Britain used brass cartridge cases for all calibres up to 6 inches in the late 1880s and early 1890s.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/rifled-breech-loader] However, British-designed quickfiring ("QF" in British terminology, which became synonymous with charges in metal cartridge cases) continued to use screw breech blocks, but with their function merely to lock the cartridge in place rather than provide obturation.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/rifled-breech-loader] The powerful backward force generated by 6-inch QF guns still required a strongly seated breech screw with as much thread as possible.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/rifled-breech-loader] However, a basic interrupted-thread screw sufficiently long enough to have enough thread to secure the cartridge on firing still required three separate motions to operate – rotate, withdraw, swing aside after firing, and repeated in reverse before firing.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/rifled-breech-loader] Elswick Ordnance Company (Armstrong's ordnance arm) developed a coned version of the interrupted-thread screw, with a decreasing rather than constant diameter towards the front.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/rifled-breech-loader] This eliminated the second "withdrawal" motion, with just two motions now necessary, rotate and swing aside.
[src:rifled-breech-loader/rifled-breech-loader] This proved short-lived, with Britain adopting charges in bags using the Welin stepped interrupted screw for all guns 5 in (130 mm) and up within several years of it becoming available.
